<chapter xml:id="chapter-funcs" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Functions</title>

<section xml:id="section-funcs-basics">
<title>Basics</title>

<subsection>
<title>Terminology and basic concepts</title>

<p><dl width="narrow">
	<li xml:id="definition-funcs-working">
		<title>function (working definition)</title>
		<!-- \label{DEFN::function.working.defn} -->
		<idx><h>function</h><h>definition</h><h>working</h></idx>
		<p> a rule which assigns to each input element from a set <m>A</m> a single output element from a set <m>B</m> </p>
	</li>
	<li xml:id="definition-funcs-domain">
		<title>domain</title>
		<idx>domain (of a function)</idx>
		<idx><h>function</h><h>domain</h></idx>
		<p> the set of all possible input elements for a function </p>
	</li>
	<li xml:id="definition-funcs-codomain">
		<title>codomain</title>
		<idx>codomain (of a function)</idx>
		<idx><h>function</h><h>codomain</h></idx>
		<p> a set <em>containing</em> all possible output elements for a function </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title><m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m></usage>
			<description><m>f</m> is a function with domain <m>A</m> and codomain <m>B</m></description>
		</notation>
		<p> <m>f</m> is a function with domain <m>A</m> and codomain <m>B</m> </p>
	</li>
	<li xml:id="definition-funcs-rule">
		<title>input-output rule</title>
		<idx>input-output rule (of a function)</idx>
		<idx><h>function</h><h>input-output rule</h></idx>
		<p> the process/algorithm/rule/formula that describes how each input element from the domain will be transformed into an output element in the codomain </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title><m>f(a) = b</m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>f(a) = b</m></usage>
			<description>function <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m> associates the codomain element <m>b\in B</m> to the domain element <m>a\in A</m></description>
		</notation>
		<p> function <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m> associates the codomain element <m>b\in B</m> to the domain element <m>a\in A</m> </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title><m>a \mapsto b</m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>a \mapsto b</m></usage>
			<description>alternative notation for <m>f(a) = b</m></description>
		</notation>
		<p> alternative notation for <m>f(a) = b</m> </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>image (of an domain element)</title>
		<idx><h>image</h><h>of a domain element</h></idx>
		<idx><h>element</h><h>image under a function</h></idx>
		<p>
		when <m>f(a) = b</m> we say that <m>b</m> is the <term>image</term> of <m>a</m> under <m>f</m>,
		or that <m>f</m> <term>maps</term> <m>a</m> to <m>b</m>
		</p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<figure>
	<caption>A Venn diagram of a function transforming a domain element into a codomain element.</caption>
	<image xml:id="image-funcs-func-def" width="42.6%">
		<description>A Venn diagram of a function transforming a domain element into a codomain element.</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/func-def.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<warning>
	<title>Domain elements are necessarily inputs, but codomain elements are not necessarily outputs</title>
	<p>
	When we define a function,
	the domain should either be implicitly clear from the <xref ref="definition-funcs-rule" text="title" />,
	or explicitly stated so that the precise collection of allowable input elements is known.
	</p><p>
	However, it would be too onerous to do the same for the precise collection of output elements <mdash />
	often when we create a function we won't initially know exactly what outputs it will produce.
	The purpose of stating a <term>codomain</term> is so that it is at least clear what <em>type</em> of output element is produced.
	</p>
</warning>

</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>Defining functions</title>

<p>
Defining a function is a <alert>two-step process</alert>,
in which we need to specify <alert>three pieces of information</alert>:
<ol marker="(i)">
	<li> the <term><xref ref="definition-funcs-domain" text="title" /></term>, </li>
	<li> the <term><xref ref="definition-funcs-codomain" text="title" /></term>, and </li>
	<li> the <term><xref ref="definition-funcs-rule" text="title" /></term>. </li>
</ol>
</p><p>
The first two pieces of information are specified in one step,
when we write
<me> \funcdef{f}{A}{B} </me>.
This notation indicates that <m>A</m> will be the domain and <m>B</m> will be the codomain for the function named <m>f</m>.
Of course, the <term>name</term> of the function is an additional piece of information being specified with this notation,
but naming a function is optional (though highly recommended!).
</p><p>
Specifying the input-output rule may be done in many different ways, <eg /> by a formula, table of values, a description of a step-by-step process or algorithm to determine or compute an output given an arbitrary input, <etc /> <!-- <etc /> already outputs a period -->
</p>

<example><title>Defining a function by an input-output formula</title><p>
	An input-output formula like <m>f(x) = \sqrt{x}</m> defines a function,
	but we here need to be careful about the domain.
	The domain and codomain for this function could be specified as <m>\funcdef{f}{\nnegset{\R}}{\R}</m>,
	where <m>\nnegset{\R}</m> represents the set of nonnegative real numbers.
</p></example>

<example>
	<title>Correctly stating a domain and codomain</title>
	<p>
	In the function definition
	<md>
		<mrow> f\colon \R \amp \to \R, </mrow>
		<mrow> x \amp \mapsto \frac{1}{x^2}, </mrow>
	</md>
	the first line of the definition tells us the <term><xref ref="definition-funcs-domain" text="title" /></term> (<m>\R</m>),
	<term><xref ref="definition-funcs-codomain" text="title" /></term> (again <m>\R</m>),
	and a name for the function (<m>f</m>).
	The second line tells us the <term><xref ref="definition-funcs-rule" text="title" /></term>,
	so that <me> f(x) = \frac{1}{x^2} </me>.
	</p><p>
	However, on closer inspection we discover that the domain has been <alert>incorrectly</alert> specified,
	as <m>x=0</m> is not a permissible input for the input-output rule.
	Instead, we should write <me> \funcdef{f}{\R \relcmplmnt \{0\}}{\R} </me>.
	</p><p>
	Even though this function will only ever produce <em>positive</em> real numbers as outputs,
	the codomain is acceptable as stated.
	It <em>would</em> be more precise to write
	<me> \funcdef{f}{\R \relcmplmnt \{0\}}{\posset{\R}}, </me>
	where <m>\posset{\R}</m> represents the set of positive real numbers,
	but it is not necessary to do so.
	</p>
</example>

<example xml:id="example-funcs-defining-by-algorithm">
	<title>Defining a function by an input-output algorithm</title>
	<p> Consider the function <m>\powset{\Z} \to \N</m> where outputs are computed according to the following algorithm. </p>
	<p>
	Given an input element <m>X \in \powset{\Z}</m> (which, by definition, is a <em>set</em> of integers), carry out the following.
	<ol>
		<li>
			Compute the absolute value of each element in <m>X</m>.
			(If <m>X</m> is empty, skip this step.)
		</li>
		<li>
			Determine the minimum result of the absolute value computations in the previous step.
			(If <m>X</m> is empty, there will not be any absolute value computation results to compare, so take <m>0</m> as the <q>mininum</q> instead.)
		</li>
		<li>
			Multiply the minimum value found in the previous step by <m>2</m> and add <m>1</m>.
			Output this final result.
		</li>
	</ol>
	However, with the right notation, an algorithm like the above can often be converted into an input-output formula <mdash />
	see <xref ref="example-funcs-comp-of-three" />.
	</p>
</example>

<!-- all these examples were formerly listed under \label{EXAMPLES::basic.func.exmps} -->
<example xml:id="example-funcs-define-by-listing">
	<!-- \label{EXAMPLES::basic.func.exmps::finite.sets} -->
	<title>Defining a function by listing input-ouput pairs</title>
	<p>
	For <m>\mathscr{N} = \{1,2,3\}</m> and <m>\mathscr{A} = \{a,b,c,d\}</m>,
	one way to define a function <m>\funcdef{f}{\mathscr{N}}{\mathscr{A}}</m> is
	<md><mrow> f(1) \amp = d, \amp f(2) \amp = a, \amp f(3) \amp = d. </mrow></md>
	</p>
</example>

<example xml:id="example-funcs-define-multivariable">
	<title>Multi-variable functions</title>
	<p>
	In a first course in calculus a student typically studies only <term>single-variable functions</term>,
	<ie /> functions with a single input variable and a single output variable.
	In subsequent calculus courses a student may study <term>multi-variable functions</term> with multiple input variables, such as
	<me> f(x,y) = x^2 + y^2 </me>.
	Technically, we should write
	<me> f\bbrac{(x,y)} = x^2 + y^2 </me>,
	as the proper definition of <m>f</m> is <m>\funcdef{f}{\R^2}{\R}</m>,
	but the extra brackets convey no additional information and only clutter things up.
	</p><p>
	Functions with multiple real output variables are often called <term>vector functions</term>.
	For example, <m>\funcdef{g}{\R}{\R^2}</m> defined by
	<me> g(t) = (t,t^2) </me>
	can be considered as a vector parametrization of a parabola in the plane.
	</p><p>
	And of course we could consider <term>multi-variable vector functions</term> as well.
	A function <m>\funcdef{\varphi}{\R^2}{\R^2}</m> like
	<me> \varphi(s,t) = (s-t,s+t) </me>
	could be considered as a change of variables
	<md><mrow> x \amp = s - t, \amp y \amp = s + t. </mrow></md>
	</p>
</example>

<example><title>Logical statements as functions</title><p>
	A logical statement <m>S</m> involving statement variables <m>p_1, p_2, \dotsc, p_m</m> is essentially a multi-variable function
	<me> \funcdef{S}{\Lambda^m}{\Lambda} </me>,
	where <m>\Lambda = \{ \lgctrue,\, \lgcfalse \}</m>.
	For example, the statement
	<me> S(p_1,p_2) = (p_1 \lgccond p_2) </me> is a function <m>\funcdef{S}{\Lambda \cartprod \Lambda}{\Lambda}</m>,
	where
	<md><mrow>
		S(\lgctrue,\lgctrue) \amp = \lgctrue, \amp
		S(\lgctrue,\lgcfalse) \amp = \lgcfalse, \amp
		S(\lgcfalse,\lgctrue) \amp = \lgctrue, \amp
		S(\lgcfalse,\lgcfalse) \amp = \lgctrue.
	</mrow></md>
</p></example>

</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsection-funcs-graph">
<title>Graph of a function</title>

<p><dl width="narrow">
	<li xml:id="definition-funcs-graph">
		<title>graph (of a function)</title>
		<idx><h>graph</h><h>of a function</h></idx>
		<idx><h>function</h><h>graph</h></idx>
		<p> the set of all input-output pairs for the function </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title><m>\funcgraph{f}</m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>\funcgraph{f}</m></usage>
			<description>graph of function <m>f</m></description>
		</notation>
		<p>
			the graph of function <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m>,
			so that
			<me> \funcgraph{f} = \setdef{(a,f(a))}{a \in A} \subseteq A \cartprod B </me>
		</p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<example>
	<title>Graph of a single-variable, real-valued function</title>
	<p>
	The graph of a function <m>\funcdef{f}{\R}{\R}</m> is a subset of <m>\R \cartprod \R = \R^2</m>.
	We usually represent <m>\R^2</m> visually as the <m>xy</m>-plane
	and the graph <m>\funcgraph{f} \subseteq \R^2</m> as a curve in the plane.
	</p>
	<figure>
		<caption>The graph <m>\funcgraph{x \mapsto x^2}</m> represented as a curve in the Cartesian plane.</caption>
		<image xml:id="image-funcs-graph-x-squared" width="36.7%">
			<description>The graph <m>\funcgraph{x \mapsto x^2}</m> represented as a curve in the Cartesian plane.</description>
			<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/graph-x-squared.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
		</image>
	</figure>
	<p>
	In the graph of <m>f(x) = x^2</m> above, each point on the curve represents an element of <m>\R^2</m> which is in the subset <m>\funcgraph{f}</m>.
	For example, <m>(-1,1) \in \funcgraph{f}</m> but <m>(-1,\pi) \notin \funcgraph{f}</m>.
	</p>
</example>

<example>
	<title>Graph of a multi-variable, real-valued function</title>
	<p>
	The graph of a function <m>\funcdef{f}{\R^2}{\R}</m> is technically a subset of <m>\R^2 \cartprod \R</m>,
	but usually we just think of this as <m>\R^3</m>, or <m>3</m>-space.
	Instead of a curve, such a graph defines a <em>surface</em> in <m>\R^3</m>.
	For example, the graph of the function <m>f(x,y) = x^2 + y^2</m> from
	<xref ref="example-funcs-define-multivariable" />
	is a parabolic cone, <ie /> a (non-solid) cone-like surface with parabolic sides.
	</p>
</example>

<example>
	<title>Graph of a function defined by a list</title>
	<p>
	To describe the graph of the function <m>\funcdef{f}{\mathscr{N}}{\mathscr{A}}</m> defined in
	<xref ref="example-funcs-define-by-listing" />,
	we just need to collect the defined input-output pairs into Cartesian product elements:
	<me> \funcgraph{f} = \{ (1,d), (2,a), (3,d) \} </me>.
	This graph can most simply be represented by a table:
	</p>
	<tabular top="medium" bottom="medium" halign="center">
		<col right="minor" /><col /><col /><col />
		<row bottom="minor">
			<cell><m>x</m></cell>
			<cell><m>1</m></cell>
			<cell><m>2</m></cell>
			<cell><m>3</m></cell>
		</row>
		<row>
			<cell><m>f(x)</m></cell>
			<cell><m>d</m></cell>
			<cell><m>a</m></cell>
			<cell><m>d</m></cell>
		</row>
	</tabular>
	<p>
	Similarly to <xref ref="example-sets-visualize-cartesian-prod" />,
	we can also visualize this graph as a set of <q>points</q> relative to a set of perpendicular <q>axes,</q>
	where the horizontal axis represents the domain set and the vertical axis represents the codomain set.
	</p>
	<tabular halign="center">
		<col /><col /><col /><col /><col />
		<row><cell><m>\mathscr{A}</m></cell></row>
		<row>
			<cell right="medium"><m>d</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\bullet</m></cell>
			<cell />
			<cell><m>\bullet</m></cell>
		</row>
		<row><cell right="medium"><m>c</m></cell></row>
		<row><cell right="medium"><m>b</m></cell></row>
		<row bottom="medium">
			<cell right="medium"><m>a</m></cell>
			<cell />
			<cell><m>\bullet</m></cell>
			<cell />
		</row>
		<row>
			<cell right="medium" />
			<cell><m>1</m></cell>
			<cell><m>2</m></cell>
			<cell><m>3</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\mathscr{N}</m></cell>
		</row>
	</tabular>
	<p>
	Notice that we have not joined the points in the above visualization with lines or a curve,
	since the three points pictured are the <em>only</em> points on the graph.
	</p>
</example>

<example>
	<title>Graph of a logical statement</title>
	<p>
	We've already encountered the graph of a logical statement:
	it is usually represented as a truth table.
	For example, the graph <m>\funcgraph{S}</m> of the logical statement
	<md><mrow>
		S \colon \Lambda \cartprod \Lambda \amp \to \Lambda, \amp
		S(p_1,p_2) \amp = p_1 \lgccond p_2,
	</mrow></md>
	where <m>\Lambda = \{ \lgctrue, \lgcfalse \}</m> as usual,
	can be represented as below.
	</p>
	<figure>
		<caption>The graph <m>\funcgraph{S}</m> of the logical statement <m>S(p_1,p_2) = p_1 \lgccond p_2</m>.</caption>
		<tabular halign="center">
			<col /><col right="minor" /><col />
			<row bottom="minor">
				<cell><m>p_1</m></cell>
				<cell><m>p_2</m></cell>
				<cell><m>S(p_1,p_2)</m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			</row><row>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgcfalse</m></cell>
				<cell><m>\lgctrue</m></cell>
			</row>
		</tabular>
	</figure>
</example>

<p>
Unfortunately,
our <xref ref="definition-funcs-working" text="custom">working definition</xref>
for <term>function</term> is lacking:
what is a <q>rule</q>?
Rather than chasing some circle of definitions, we can come up with a better definition by noticing that the graph of a function contains all the necessary information about the function.
</p>

<p><dl width="narrow">
	<li xml:id="definition-funcs-formal">
		<title>function (formal definition)</title>
		<idx><h>function</h><h>definition</h><h>formal</h></idx>
		<p>
		a subset <m>F \subseteq A \cartprod B</m> such that for every <m>x\in A</m> there is <em>exactly one</em> element <m>(a,b)\in F</m> with <m>a=x</m>
		</p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<p>
In this formal definition, we are defining a function to <em>be</em> what we previously would have called its <term>graph</term>.
</p>

<example>
	<title>Formal definition for a single-variable, real-valued function</title>
	<p>
	We are now defining a function <m>\funcdef{f}{\R}{\R}</m> to be the subset of the Cartesian plane <m>\R^2</m> consisting of the graph of the function.
	In this case, you can think of the <q>exactly one</q> requirement as equivalent to the <term>vertical line test</term>:
	an input value may not produce more than one output value.
	(Though the <q>one</q> part of <q>exactly one</q> captures our requirement that a function be defined on every domain element.)
	</p>
</example>

</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>Undefined and well-defined</title>

<p>
We have to be careful defining functions;
sometimes what we think is a function turns out to not be a function.
</p>

<!--
	\label{EXAMPLES::nonfunctions::both}
    .... the next two examples used to be combined into one example, with the above label
-->

<example xml:id="example-funcs-undefined">
	<title>A function must be defined on the whole domain</title>
	<idx><h>function</h><h>undefined on domain element</h></idx>
	<p>
	Again write  <m>\mathscr{N} = \{1,2,3\}</m> and <m>\mathscr{A} = \{a,b,c,d\}</m>,
	and consider
	<me> F = \{ (1,a), (3,d) \} \subseteq \mathscr{N} \cartprod \mathscr{A} </me>.
	Does this subset define a function with domain <m>\mathscr{N}</m> and codomain <m>\mathscr{A}</m>?
	That is, does there exist a function <m>\funcdef{f}{\mathscr{N}}{\mathscr{A}}</m> such that <m>F = \funcgraph{f}</m>?
	The answer is <alert>no</alert>, because there is no input-output pair in <m>F</m> with domain element <m>2</m>.
	If we attempt to consider a function <m>f</m> with graph <m>\funcgraph{f} = F</m>,
	we have no way to tell what result <m>f(2)</m> should return.
	In other words, such an <m>f</m> will have been left
	<term>undefined</term> on element <m>2</m>, which is supposed to be part of the domain.
	</p><p>
	The set <m>F</m> <em>does</em> define a function, just not one with domain <m>\mathscr{N}</m>.
	If we consider the smaller set <m>\mathscr{N}' = \{1,3\}</m>,
	then there <em>is</em> a function <m>\funcdef{f}{\mathscr{N}'}{\mathscr{A}}</m> with <m>F = \funcgraph{f}</m>.
	</p>
</example>

<example xml:id="example-funcs-well-defined">
	<title>A function must be <term>well-defined</term></title>
	<idx><h>function</h><h>well-defined</h></idx>
	<p>
	Again write  <m>\mathscr{N} = \{1,2,3\}</m> and <m>\mathscr{A} = \{a,b,c,d\}</m>,
	and consider
	<me> F = \{ (1,a), (3,a), (3,d) \} \subseteq \mathscr{N} \cartprod \mathscr{A} </me>.
	Does this subset define a function with domain <m>\mathscr{N}</m> and codomain <m>\mathscr{A}</m>?
	That is, does there exist a function <m>\funcdef{f}{\mathscr{N}}{\mathscr{A}}</m> such that <m>F = \funcgraph{f}</m>?
	The answer is <alert>no</alert>, because there are <em>more than one</em> input-output pairs with domain element <m>3</m>.
	In other words, a function <m>f</m> with graph <m>\funcgraph{f} = F</m> is not <term>well-defined</term>,
	because we have no way to tell whether <m>f(3)</m> should be <m>a</m> or <m>d</m>.
	</p>
</example>

<example>
	<!-- \label{EXAMPLES::nonfunctions::not.well.defined} -->
	<title>An input-output rule does not necessarily define a function</title>
	<p>
	Recall that
	<me> \Q = \setdef{\frac{m}{n}}{ m,n\in \Z,\, n\ne 0}</me>.
	Suppose we attempt to define <m>\funcdef{f}{\Q}{\Z}</m> by <m>f(\frac{m}{n}) = m+n</m>.
	This seems like a valid way to define a function, until we realize that, for example,
	<md><mrow>
		f\left(\frac{1}{2}\right) \amp = 1 + 2 = 3, \amp
		f\left(\frac{2}{4}\right) \amp = 2 + 4 = 6.
	</mrow></md>
	This is nonsense, because <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> and <m>\frac{2}{4}</m> represent the <em>same element</em> of <m>\Q</m>.
	Thus, rule <m>f</m> is not well-defined as a function, since to each element of the domain <m>\Q</m> it associates more than one element of the codomain <m>\Z</m>.
	</p>
</example>

</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>Equality of functions</title>

<p><dl width="narrow"><li xml:id="definition-funcs-equality">
	<title>equality of functions</title>
	<!-- \label{DEFN::func.equality} -->
	<idx><h>equality</h><h>of functions</h></idx>
	<idx><h>function</h><h>equality</h></idx>
	<p>
	for <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m> and <m>\funcdef{g}{A}{B}</m>,
	write <m>f = g</m> if <m>f(a) = g(a)</m> for all <m>a\in A</m>
	</p>
</li></dl></p>

<example>
	<title>Seemingly different input-output rules can define the same function</title>
	<p>
	The functions <m>\funcdef{f}{\R}{\R}</m>, <m>f(x) = \abs{x}</m>, and <m>\funcdef{g}{\R}{\R}</m>, <m>g(x) = \sqrt{x^2}</m>, are equal.
	</p>
</example>

</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>Image of a function</title>

<p><dl width="narrow">
	<li>
		<title>image of a function</title>
		<!-- \label{DEFN::image} -->
		<idx><h>image</h><h>of a function</h></idx>
		<idx><h>function</h><h>image</h></idx>
		<p> the set of all possible outputs of the function </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title><m>f(A)</m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>f(A)</m></usage>
			<description>the image of function <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m></description>
		</notation>
		<p>
		the image of function <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m>,
		so that <me> f(A) = \setdef{f(a)}{a \in A} \subseteq B </me>
		</p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<figure>
	<caption>A Venn diagram of the image of a function.</caption>
	<image xml:id="image-funcs-image" width="64.1%">
		<description>A Venn diagram of the image of a function.</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/image.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<warning>
	<title>Codomain elements are not necessarily image elements</title>
	<p>
	We have stated before that a codomain in a function definition may be <q>larger</q> than necessary because we do not always know precisely what output elements a given input-output rule will produce.
	Our idea of codomain is that it should at least tell us what <q>type</q> of outputs will be produced, but not necessarily <em>exactly</em> what outputs will be produced.
	</p><p>
	With our new concept of <term>function image</term>, we can now repeat this more technically:
	<alert>
		a function image is always a subset of the codomain, but it might be a
		<xref ref="definition-sets-proper-subset" text="title" />
	</alert>.
	</p>
</warning>

<paragraphs><title>How do we know if a codomain element is an image element?</title><p>
	For function <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m> and codomain element <m>b\in B</m>,
	we have <m>b \in f(A)</m> if and only if there exists <m>a\in A</m> such that <m>b = f(a)</m>.
</p></paragraphs>

<problem xml:id="wexample-funcs-verify-function-image"> <!-- worked example -->
	<title>Verifying a function image description</title>
	<statement><p>
		Consider <m>\funcdef{f}{\R}{\R}</m>, <m>f(x) = x^2</m>.
		Prove <m>f(\R) = \nnegset{\R}</m>, where <m>\nnegset{\R}</m> is the set of nonnegative real numbers.
	</p></statement>
	<solution>
		<p>
		Following the <xref ref="test-sets-equality" text="custom">Test for Set Equality</xref>,
		we need to show both
		<md><mrow> f(\R) \amp \subseteq \nnegset{\R}, \amp f(\R) \amp \supseteq \nnegset{\R} </mrow></md>.
		To be more explicit about the second set <m>\nnegset{\R}</m>,
		we can write
		<me> \nnegset{\R} = \setdef{x\in \R}{x \ge 0} </me>.
		</p>
		<case><title>Show <m>f(\R) \subseteq \nnegset{\R}</m></title><p>
			Let <m>y</m> represent an <em>arbitrary</em> element of <m>f(\R)</m>.
			As an element of the image of <m>f</m>, <m>y</m> is an output corresponding to some input.
			That is, there exists some <m>x \in \R</m> such that <me> y = f(x) = x^2 </me>.
			Therefore, since square numbers are always positive, we have <m>y \ge 0</m>, and hence <m>y \in \nnegset{\R}</m>.
		</p></case>
		<case><title>Show <m>f(\R) \supseteq \nnegset{\R}</m></title><p>
			Let <m>y</m> represent an <em>arbitrary</em> element of <m>\nnegset{\R}</m>.
			To show <m>y \in f(\R)</m>, we need to find <m>x \in \R</m> such that <m>f(x) = y</m>.
			Let <m>x = \sqrt{y}</m>, which is defined since <m>y \in \nnegset{\R}</m> implies <m>y\ge 0</m>.
			Then <me> f(x) = x^2 = (\sqrt{y})^2 = y </me>, as desired.
		</p></case>
	</solution>
</problem>

<p><dl width="narrow">
	<li xml:id="definition-funcs-image-on-subset">
		<title>image of a function on a subset</title>
		<idx><h>image</h><h>of a function on a subset</h></idx>
		<idx><h>subset</h><h>image under a function</h></idx>
		<idx><h>function</h><h>image</h><h>on a subset</h></idx>
		<p> the set of all outputs of a function when only fed inputs from a given subset </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title><m>f(A')</m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>f(A')</m></usage>
			<description>the image of function <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m> on a subset <m>A' \subseteq A</m></description>
		</notation>
		<p>
		the image of the subset <m>A' \subseteq A</m> under a function <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m>,
		so that <me> f(A') = \setdef{f(a)}{a \in A'} \subseteq B </me>
		</p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<example><p>
	We saw in <xref ref="wexample-funcs-verify-function-image" /> that for
	<m>\funcdef{f}{\R}{\R}</m>, <m>f(x) = x^2</m>, we have <m>f(\R) = \nnegset{\R}</m>.
	Now, the set of integers <m>\Z</m> is a subset of the domain <m>\R</m>, so we can compute
	<me> f(\Z) = \{0,1,4,9,16,\dotsc,n^2,\dotsc\} \subseteq \nnegset{\R} </me>.
</p></example>

</subsection>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-funcs-properties">
<title>Properties of functions</title>

<p><dl width="narrow">
	<li>
		<title>surjective function</title>
		<idx><h>function</h><h>surjective</h></idx>
		<p>
		a function whose image is all of its codomain <mdash />
		that is, every element of the codomain is an output for the function;
		</p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>surjection</title>
		<idx>surjection</idx>
		<p> a surjective function </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>onto</title>
		<idx><h>function</h><h>onto</h></idx>
		<idx>onto</idx>
		<p> synonym for surjective </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title><m>\sfuncdef{f}{A}{B}</m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>\sfuncdef{f}{A}{B}</m></usage>
			<description>function <m>f</m> is surjective</description>
		</notation>
		<p> function <m>f</m> is surjective </p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<p>
A function <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m> is surjective if <m>f(A) = B</m>.
Since we have <m>f(A) \subseteq B</m> by definition of image, to show that a function is surjective we only need to show <m>f(A) \supseteq B</m>.
</p>

<claim xml:id="test-funcs-surj">
	<title>Surjective function</title>
	<idx><h>Test</h><h>surjective function</h></idx>
	<idx><h>function</h><h>surjective</h><h>Test</h></idx>
	<statement><p><ul>
		<li>
			Function <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m> is surjective if <m>B \subseteq f(A)</m>.
			That is, <m>f</m> is surjective if <em>for every</em> element <m>b \in B</m>,
			there exists <em>at least one</em> element <m>a \in A</m> such that <m>f(a) = b</m>.
		</li><li>
			Function <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m> is <em>not</em> surjective if there exists <em>at least one</em> element <m>b \in B</m> for which there is <em>no</em> element <m>a \in A</m> satisfying <m>f(a) = b</m>.
			(Equivalently, there exists <m>b \in B</m> for which every <m>a \in A</m> satisifes <m>f(a) \neq b</m>.)
		</li>
	</ul></p></statement>
</claim>

<problem> <!-- worked example -->
	<statement><p>
		Show that, of the following functions, <m>f</m> is surjective and <m>g</m> is not.
		<md>
			<mrow> f \colon \Z \amp \to \N \amp g \colon \Z \amp \to \Q </mrow>
			<mrow> m \amp \mapsto \abs{m} \amp m \amp \mapsto m/2 </mrow>
		</md>
	</p></statement>
	<solution>
		<case><title>Show that <m>f</m> is surjective</title><p>
			Consider an <em>arbitrary</em> element <m>n</m> of the codomain <m>\N</m>.
			Since <m>\N \subseteq \Z</m>, <m>n</m> is also an element of the domain.
			In particular, <m>f(n) = n</m>, since <m>n\ge 0</m>.
			Therefore, as an element of the codomain, we have <m>n\in f(\Z)</m>.
		</p></case>
		<case><title>Show that <m>g</m> is not surjective</title><p>
			We need to find a <em>specific</em> example of a rational number that is not an output for <m>g</m>.
			For this, we could use <m>1/3</m>, since there is no integer such that <m>m/2 = 1/3</m>.
		</p></case>
	</solution>
</problem>

<p><dl width="narrow">
	<li>
		<title>injective function</title>
		<idx><h>function</h><h>injective</h></idx>
		<p> a function for which two different inputs <em>never</em> produce the same output </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>injection</title>
		<idx>injection</idx>
		<p> an injective function </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>embedding</title>
		<idx><h>function</h><h>embedding</h></idx>
		<idx>embedding</idx>
		<p> synonym for injection </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>one-to-one</title>
		<idx><h>function</h><h>one-to-one</h></idx>
		<idx>one-to-one</idx>
		<p> synonym for injective </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title><m>\ifuncdef{f}{A}{B}</m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>\ifuncdef{f}{A}{B}</m></usage>
			<description>function <m>f</m> is injective</description>
		</notation>
		<p> function <m>f</m> is injective </p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<claim xml:id="test-funcs-inj">
	<title>Injective function</title>
	<idx><h>Test</h><h>injective function</h></idx>
	<idx><h>function</h><h>injective</h><h>Test</h></idx>
	<statement><p><ul>
		<li>
			<p>
			Function <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m> is injective if the following conditional always holds for elements <m>a_1,a_2 \in A</m>:
			</p>
			<blockquote><p> if <m>a_1 \ne a_2</m> then <m>f(a_1) \ne f(a_2)</m>. </p></blockquote>
			<p>
			Alternatively, one can establish that the
			<xref ref="definition-logic-equiv-contrapositive" text="title" />
			of the above conditional always holds for elements <m>a_1,a_2 \in A</m>:
			</p>
			<blockquote><p> if <m>f(a_1) = f(a_2)</m> then <m>a_1 = a_2</m>. </p></blockquote>
		</li><li>
			Function <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m> is <em>not</em> injective if there exists <em>at least one</em> pair of elements <m>a_1,a_2 \in A</m> with <m>a_1 \ne a_2</m> but <m>f(a_1) = f(a_2)</m>.
		</li>
	</ul></p></statement>
</claim>

<example>
	<title>Demonstrating that a function is not injective</title>
	<p>
	The function <m>\funcdef{f}{\R}{\R}</m>, <m>f(x) = x^2</m>, is <em>not</em> injective,
	since <m>f</m> has repeated outputs.
	For example, <m>f(-1) = f(1)</m>.
	And in fact, <m>f(-x) = f(x)</m> for every <m>x\in \R</m>.
	</p>
</example>

<problem> <!-- worked example -->
	<title>Demonstrating that a function is injective</title>
	<statement><p>
		Verify that the function <m>\funcdef{f}{\N}{\N}</m>, <m>f(n) = 2n+1</m>, is injective.
	</p></statement>
	<solution><p>
		Using the contrapositive version of the
		<xref ref="test-funcs-inj" text="custom">Injective Function Test</xref>,
		suppose domain elements <m>n_1,n_2 \in \N</m> satisfy <m>f(n_1) = f(n_2)</m>.
		Then using the formula defining the input-output rule for <m>f</m>,
		we have <me> 2 n_1 + 1 = 2 n_2 + 1 </me>,
		which reduces to <m>n_1 = n_2</m>.
	</p></solution>
</problem>

<p>
An injection <m>\ifuncdef{f}{A}{B}</m> gives us a way of thinking of <m>A</m> as a <em>subset</em> of <m>B</m>,
by considering <m>f(A) \subseteq B</m>.
</p>

<example xml:id="example-funcs-letters-embed-into-numbers">
	<title>Turning letters into numbers</title>
	<p> Let <m>\Sigma = \ShortEngAlphabet</m>, and define <m>\funcdef{\varphi}{\Sigma}{\N}</m> by the following table. </p>
	<tabular top="medium" bottom="medium" halign="center">
		<col right="minor" /><col /><col /><col /><col /><col />
		<row>
			<cell><m>\sigma</m></cell>
			<cell><m>a</m></cell>
			<cell><m>b</m></cell>
			<cell><m>c</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\cdots</m></cell>
			<cell><m>z</m></cell>
		</row>
		<row>
			<cell><m>\varphi(\sigma)</m></cell>
			<cell><m>1</m></cell>
			<cell><m>2</m></cell>
			<cell><m>3</m></cell>
			<cell><m>\cdots</m></cell>
			<cell><m>26</m></cell>
		</row>
	</tabular>
	<p> Then <m>f</m> <term>embeds</term> <m>\Sigma</m> into <m>\N</m> in a familiar way, and lets us think of letters as numbers. </p>
</example>

<p><dl width="narrow">
	<li xml:id="definition-funcs-bijective">
		<title>bijective function</title>
		<idx><h>function</h><h>bijective</h></idx>
		<p> a function that is both injective and surjective </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>bijection</title>
		<idx>bijection</idx>
		<p> an bijective function </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title>one-to-one correspondence</title>
		<idx><h>function</h><h>one-to-one</h></idx>
		<idx>one-to-one</idx>
		<p> synonym for bijection </p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<example><p> Function <m>\funcdef{f}{\R}{\R}</m>, <m>f(x) = x^3</m> is bijective. </p></example>

<p> A bijection <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m> allows us to think of <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> as essentially the same sets. </p>

<example xml:id="example-func-identify-letters-numbers">
	<title>Identifying letters with numbers</title>
	<p>
	Consider again <m>\funcdef{f}{\Sigma}{\N}</m> from
	<xref ref="example-funcs-letters-embed-into-numbers" />.
	If we write <m>B = f(\Sigma) = \{1,2,3,\dotsc,26\}</m>,
	then really we could think of the function as being defined <m>\funcdef{f}{\Sigma}{B}</m>.
	This version of <m>f</m> is bijective, and allows us to identify each letter with a corresponding number:
	<md><mrow>
		a \amp \leftrightarrow 1,
		\amp b \amp \leftrightarrow 2,
		\amp c \amp \leftrightarrow 3,
		\amp \amp \dotsc,
		\amp z \amp \leftrightarrow 26.
	</mrow></md>
	In this way, we can think of <m>\Sigma</m> and <m>B</m> as essentially the same set.
	</p>
</example>

<problem> <!-- worked example -->
	<title>Recognizing bijections</title>
	<statement><p>
		Which of the following functions are bijections?
		<md>
			<mrow>
				f \colon \Z \amp \to \Z,
				\amp g \colon \Z \amp \to \N,
				\amp h \colon \Z \amp \to \Z,
			</mrow><mrow>
				m \amp\mapsto 2m,
				\amp m \amp \mapsto \abs{m},
				\amp m \amp \mapsto -m.
			</mrow>
		</md>
	</p></statement>
	<solution>
		<case><title>Is <m>f</m> bijective?</title><p>
			No, <m>f</m> is not bijective because it is not surjective.
			For example, there is no <m>m\in \Z</m> such that <m>f(m) = 1</m>.
		</p></case>
		<case><title>Is <m>g</m> bijective?</title><p>
			No, <m>g</m> is not bijective because it is not injective.
			For example, <m>g(-1) = g(1)</m>.
		</p></case>
		<case><title>Is <m>h</m> bijective?</title><p>
			Yes, <m>h</m> is bijective.
			It is injective because if <m>m_1 \ne m_2</m> then <m>-m_1 \ne -m_2</m>.
			And it is surjective because for <m>n\in \Z</m>, we can realize <m>n</m> as an output <m>n = h(m)</m> by setting <m>m = -n</m>.
		</p></case>
	</solution>
</problem>

<exercise><title>Bijections of counting sets</title><p>
	<!-- \label{TYU::counting.sets} -->
	For <m>m \in \N</m> write
	<me> \natnumlt{m} = \setdef{n \in \N}{ n \lt m} = \{ 0,\, 1,\, \dotsc,\, m-1\} </me>.
	Prove that there exists a bijection <m>\natnumlt{\ell} \to \natnumlt{m}</m> if and only if <m>\ell = m</m>.
</p></exercise>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-funcs-important-exmps">
<title>Important examples</title>

<!-- TODO maybe group some into some sections, like:
    Identity and inclusion functions
	Restrictions
	Etc.
-->

<p><dl width="narrow">
	<li>
		<title>identity function (on a set <m>A</m>)</title>
		<idx><h>function</h><h>identity</h></idx>
		<idx>identity function</idx>
		<p> the function <m>A \to A</m> defined by <m>a \mapsto a</m> </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title><m>\funcdef{\id_A}{A}{A}</m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>\funcdef{\id_A}{A}{A}</m></usage>
			<description>the identity function on on set <m>A</m></description>
		</notation>
		<p> the identity function on on set <m>A</m> </p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<note><p> An identity function is always a bijection. </p></note>

<p><dl width="narrow">
	<li>
		<title>inclusion function (on subset <m>A \subseteq X</m>)</title>
		<idx><h>function</h><h>inclusion</h></idx>
		<idx>inclusion function</idx>
		<p> the function <m>A \to X</m> defined by <m>a \mapsto a</m> </p>
	</li>
</dl></p>
<aside><title>Check your understanding</title><p>
	Do you understand the difference between the definitions of <term>identity function</term> and <term>inclusion function</term>?
</p></aside>
<p><dl width="narrow">
	<li>
		<title><m>\funcdef{\inclfunc{A}{X}}{A}{X}</m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>\funcdef{\inclfunc{A}{X}}{A}{X}</m></usage>
			<description>the inclusion function on subset <m>A \subseteq X</m></description>
		</notation>
		<p>the inclusion function on subset <m>A \subseteq X</m></p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<note><p> An inclusion function is always an injection. </p></note>

<p><dl width="narrow">
	<li>
		<title>projection functions (on a Cartesian product <m>A \cartprod B</m>)</title>
		<idx><h>function</h><h>projection</h></idx>
		<idx><h>projection</h><h>function</h></idx>
		<p>
		the functions <m>A \cartprod B \to A</m> and <m>A \cartprod B \to B</m> defined by
		<m>(a,b) \mapsto a</m> and <m>(a,b) \mapsto b</m>
		</p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title><m>\funcdef{\projfunc{A}}{A \cartprod B}{A}</m></title>
		<p> the projection function onto the first factor <m>A</m> in the Cartesian product <m>A \cartprod B</m> </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title><m>\funcdef{\projfunc{B}}{A \cartprod B}{B}</m></title>
		<p> the projection function onto the second factor <m>B</m> in the Cartesian product <m>A \cartprod B</m> </p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<example><title>Projection images</title><p>
Consider <m>(\frac{1}{2},\pi) \in \Q \cartprod \R</m>.
Then <md><mrow> p_{\Q} \left( \frac{1}{2}, \pi \right) \amp = \frac{1}{2}, \amp  p_{\R} \left( \frac{1}{2}, \pi \right) \amp = \pi </mrow></md>.
</p></example>

<paragraphs><title>Extend</title><p>
	We may of course similarly define a projection function on a Cartesian product with any number of factors.
	Write
	<me> \funcdef{\projfunc{i}}{A_1 \cartprod A_2 \cartprod \dotsb \cartprod A_n}{A_i} </me>
	<notation>
		<usage><m>\funcdef{\projfunc{i}}{A_1 \cartprod A_2 \cartprod \dotsb \cartprod A_n}{A_i}</m></usage>
		<description>
			the projection function onto the <m>\nth[i]</m> factor <m>A_i</m> in the Cartesian product
			<me> A_1 \cartprod A_2 \cartprod \dotsb \cartprod A_n</me>
		</description>
	</notation>
	to mean the projection function onto the <m>\nth[i]</m> factor <m>A_i</m> in the Cartesian product
	<me> A_1 \cartprod A_2 \cartprod \dotsb \cartprod A_n</me>.
	Alternatively, we may write
	<me> \funcdef{\proj_i}{A_1 \cartprod A_2 \cartprod \dotsb \cartprod A_n}{A_i} </me>
	<notation>
		<usage><m>\funcdef{\proj_i}{A_1 \cartprod A_2 \cartprod \dotsb \cartprod A_n}{A_i}</m></usage>
		<description> alternative notation for <m>\projfunc{i}</m> </description>
	</notation>
	for this function.
</p></paragraphs>

<note><p>
	A projection is always surjective
	(except possibly when one or more of the factors in the Cartesian product is the empty set).
</p></note>

<!-- \label{EXAMPLE::restrict.domain} -->
<p><dl width="narrow">
	<li xml:id="definition-funcs-restricting-domain">
		<title>restricting the domain</title>
		<idx><h>restriction</h><h sortby="domain of a function">of the domain of a function</h></idx>
		<idx><h>function</h><h>restriction (of the domain)</h></idx>
		<p>
		the <q>induced</q> function <m>A \to Y</m> created from function <m>\funcdef{f}{X}{Y}</m> and subset <m>A \subseteq X</m>
		by <q>forgetting</q> about all elements of <m>X</m> that do not lie in <m>A</m>
		</p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title><m>\funcres{f}{A}</m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>\funcres{f}{A}</m></usage>
			<description> restriction of function <m>\funcdef{f}{X}{Y}</m> to subset <m>A \subseteq X</m> </description>
		</notation>
		<p> restriction of function <m>\funcdef{f}{X}{Y}</m> to subset <m>A \subseteq X</m> </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title><m>\altfuncres{f}{A}</m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>\altfuncres{f}{A}</m></usage>
			<description> alternative domain restriction notation </description>
		</notation>
		<p> alternative domain restriction notation </p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title><m>\res_A^X f</m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>\res_A^X f</m></usage>
			<description> alternative domain restriction notation </description>
		</notation>
		<p> alternative domain restriction notation </p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<figure>
	<caption>A Venn diagram of restricting the domain of a function.</caption>
	<image xml:id="image-funcs-domain-res" width="76.4%">
		<description>A Venn diagram of restricting the domain of a function.</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/domain-res.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<example><title>Domain restriction</title><p>
	For <m>\funcdef{f}{\Z}{\N}</m>, <m>f(m) = \abs{m}</m>, we have <m>\funcres{f}{\N} = \id_{\N}</m>.
</p></example>

<exercise><title>Properties of restrictions</title><p>
	Consider function <m>\funcdef{f}{X}{Y}</m> and subset <m>A \subseteq X</m>.
	<ol>
		<li> If <m>f</m> is injective, is <m>\funcres{f}{A}</m> injective? </li>
		<li> If <m>\funcres{f}{A}</m> is injective, must <m>f</m> be injective? </li>
		<li> Answer the previous two questions replacing <q>injective</q> with <q>surjective</q>. </li>
	</ol>
</p></exercise>

<remark><p>
	The concept of <term>restricting the domain</term> makes our previously defined concept
	<term><xref ref="definition-funcs-image-on-subset" text="title" /></term> unnecessary:
	for function <m>\funcdef{f}{X}{Y}</m> and subset <m>A \subseteq X</m>,
	the image of <m>f</m> on <m>A</m> is the same as the image of the restriction <m>\funcres{f}{A}</m>.
</p></remark>

<p><dl width="narrow"><li xml:id="definition-funcs-restrict-codomain">
	<title>restricting the codomain</title>
	<idx><h>restriction</h><h sortby="codomain of a function">of the codomain of a function</h></idx>
	<idx><h>function</h><h>restricting the codomain</h></idx>
	<p>
	the <q>induced</q> function <m>X \to B</m> created from function <m>\funcdef{f}{X}{Y}</m> and subset <m>B \subseteq Y</m>
	by <q>forgetting</q> about all elements of <m>Y</m> that do not lie in <m>B</m>,
	<em>where <m>B</m> must contain the image of <m>f</m></em>
	</p>
</li></dl></p>

<figure>
	<caption>A Venn diagram of restricting the codomain of a function.</caption>
	<image xml:id="image-funcs-codomain-res" width="71.1%">
		<description>A Venn diagram of restricting the codomain of a function.</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/codomain-res.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<example><title>Codomain restriction</title><p>
	Consider <m>\funcdef{f}{\R}{\R}</m>, <m>f(x) = x^2</m>.
	It would be more precise to write <m>\funcdef{f}{\R}{\nnegset{\R}}</m>,
	since <m>x^2 \ge 0</m> for all <m>x \in \R</m>.
</p></example>

<note><p>
	If we restrict the codomain all the way down to the image set <m>f(X)</m>,
	the resulting map <m>\funcdef{f}{X}{f(X)}</m> is always surjective.
	In particular, if <m>\ifuncdef{f}{X}{Y}</m> is injective, then by restricting the codomain we can obtain a <em>bijection</em> <m>\funcdef{f}{X}{f(X)}</m>.
</p></note>

<p><dl width="narrow"><li>
	<title>extension of a function</title>
	<idx>extension (of a function)</idx>
	<idx><h>function</h><h>extension</h></idx>
	<p>
	relative to function <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m> and <em>super</em>set <m>X \supseteq A</m>,
	a function <m>\funcdef{g}{X}{B}</m> so that <m>g(a) = f(a)</m> for all <m>a \in A</m>
	</p>
</li></dl></p>

<figure>
	<caption>A Venn diagram of a function extension.</caption>
	<image xml:id="image-funcs-extension" width="83.5%">
		<description>A Venn diagram of a function extension.</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/extension.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<note><p>
	The condition defining the concept <term>extension function</term> can be more succinctly stated as requiring
	function <m>\funcdef{g}{X}{B}</m> with <m>A \subseteq X</m> satisfy <m>\funcres{g}{A} = f</m>.
</p></note>

<example xml:id="example-funcs-floor-eq-extension"><title>Floor function</title><p>
	Write <m>\funcdef{\flr}{\R}{\Z}</m> to mean the <term>floor function</term>:
	for real input <m>x</m>, the output <m>\flr(x)</m> is defined to be the greatest integer that is less than or equal to <m>x</m>.
	Usually we write
	<me> \flr(x) = \floor{x} </me>.
	As every integer is less than or equal to itself, we have <m>\flr(z) = z</m> for every <m>z \in \Z</m>.
	This says that the floor function is an extension of the identity function <m>\id_{\Z}</m>.
</p></example>

<p>
One of the most common ways to extend a function to a larger domain is to pick an appropriate constant value in the codomain to assign to all <q>new</q> inputs in the enlarged domain.
</p>

<p><dl width="narrow"><li>
	<title>extenstion by zero</title>
	<idx><h>extension (of a function)</h><h>by zero</h></idx>
	<idx><h>function</h><h>extension</h><h>by zero</h></idx>
	<p>
	relative to function <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{Z}</m> and superset <m>X \supseteq A</m>,
	where <m>Z</m> is a set of <q>numbers</q> containing a zero element,
	the extension function <m>\funcdef{g}{X}{Z}</m> defined by
	<me>
		g(x) =
		\begin{cases}
			f(x)\text{,} \amp x \in X \text{,} \\
			0\text{,} \amp \text{otherwise.}
		\end{cases}
	</me>
	</p>
</li></dl></p>

<example>
	<title>Extending the identity function by zero</title>
	<p>
	Define <m>\funcdef{{\widetilde{\id}}_{\Z}}{\R}{\Z}</m> by
	<me>
		{\widetilde{\id}}_{\Z}(x) =
		\begin{cases}
			x\text{,} \amp x \in \Z \text{,} \\
			0\text{,} \amp \text{otherwise.}
		\end{cases}
	</me>
	Then <m>{\widetilde{\id}}_{\Z}</m> is the extension by zero of the identity function <m>\id_{\Z}</m>.
	</p>
	<aside><title>Compare</title><p>
		<xref ref="example-funcs-floor-eq-extension" /> also involved an extension of the identity function <m>\id_{\Z}</m> <mdash />
		was it an <term>extension by zero</term>?
	</p></aside>
</example>

</section>


<section xml:id="section-funcs-composition">
<title>Composition of functions</title>

<p><dl width="narrow">
	<li>
		<title>composition function</title>
		<idx>composition (of functions)</idx>
		<idx><h>function</h><h>composition</h></idx>
		<p>
		a function <m>A \to C</m> created from given functions <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m> and <m>\funcdef{g}{B}{C}</m>
		by <m>a \mapsto g\bbrac{f(a)}</m>

		</p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title><m>g \funccomp f</m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>g \funccomp f</m></usage>
			<description>the composition of functions <m>f</m> and <m>g</m></description>
		</notation>
		<p>
		the composition of functions <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m> and <m>\funcdef{g}{B}{C}</m>,
		so that <m>\funcdef{g \funccomp f}{A}{C}</m> by <m>(g \funccomp f)(a) = g\bbrac{f(a)}</m>
		</p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<figure>
	<caption>A Venn diagram of a function composition.</caption>
	<image xml:id="image-funcs-composition" width="92.9%">
		<description>A Venn diagram of a function composition.</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/composition.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<example><title>A composition of two functions</title><p>
	Consider the functions
	<md>
		<mrow>
			f \colon \R \amp \to \nnegset{\R},
			\amp g \colon \nnegset{\R} \amp \to \nnegset{\R},
		</mrow>
		<mrow>
			x \amp \mapsto x^2,
			\amp x \amp \mapsto \sqrt{x},
		</mrow>
	</md>
	Then we have
	<md>
		<mrow> g \funccomp f \colon \R \amp \to \nnegset{\R}, </mrow>
		<mrow> x \amp \mapsto \sqrt{x^2} = \abs{x}. </mrow>
	</md>
</p></example>

<warning><title>Composition order matters</title>
	<p>
	The notation for the composition of functions <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> involves a reversal of order, so that we write <m>g \funccomp f</m>.
	This is so that when we use this notation with input-output notation <m>(g \funccomp f)(a)</m>, the notation reminds us that <m>f</m> must first be applied to the input <m>a</m>, and then <m>g</m> is applied to the result <m>f(a)</m>.
	</p><p>
	In general, <m>f \funccomp g \ne g \funccomp f</m>.
	Usually, one of the two is not even defined, because domains and codomains of <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> will not necessarily match up in both orders.
	And when both <em>are</em> defined, the two different orders of composition usually have different domains and codomains.
	</p>
</warning>

<example><title>Comparing composition order</title><p>
	Consider functions
	<md>
		<mrow> f \colon \N \amp \to \N, \amp g \colon \N \amp \to \N, </mrow>
		<mrow> n \amp \mapsto n^2, \amp n \amp \mapsto n + 1. </mrow>
	</md>
	Then, both <m>\funcdef{f \funccomp g}{\N}{\N}</m> and <m>\funcdef{g \funccomp f}{\N}{\N}</m> are defined.
	But they are not equal, as
	<md><mrow>
		(f \funccomp g)(n) \amp = (n+1)^2 = n^2+2n+1, \amp
		(g \funccomp f)(n) \amp = n^2+1.
	</mrow></md>
</p></example>

<example><title>An undefined composition</title>
	<p>
	Consider functions
	<md>
		<mrow> \sqrtop \colon \N \amp \to \R, \amp \flr \colon \R \amp \to \Z, </mrow>
		<mrow> n \amp \mapsto \sqrt{n}, \amp x \amp \mapsto \floor{x}. </mrow>
	</md>
	(See <xref ref="example-funcs-floor-eq-extension" /> for a description of the <m>\flr</m> function.)
	</p><p>
	Then, <m>\funcdef{\flr \funccomp \sqrtop}{\N}{\Z}</m> is defined, with
	<me> (\flr \funccomp \sqrtop)(n) = \floor{\sqrt{n}} </me>.
	But <m>\sqrtop \funccomp \flr</m> is not defined,
	as the codomain of <m>\flr</m> does not match the domain of <m>\sqrtop</m>.
	In particular, <m>\flr</m> will sometimes return a negative output, and we cannot use such an output as an input in <m>\sqrtop</m>.
	</p>
</example>

<exercise><title>Properties of compositions</title><p>
	Consider functions <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m> and <m>\funcdef{g}{B}{C}</m>.
	<ol>
		<li> If <m>g \funccomp f</m> is injective, are either or both of <m>f,g</m> necessarily injective? </li>
		<li> Answer the same question as above with <q>injective</q> replaced by <q>surjective</q>. </li>
		<li> Demonstrate that if both <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> are bijective, then the composition <m>g \funccomp f</m> is also bijective. </li>
	</ol>
</p></exercise>

<p> Of course, we can compose any number of functions. </p>

<example xml:id="example-funcs-comp-of-three">
	<title>A composition of three functions</title>
	<p>
	Let us reconsider the function defined by algorithm in <xref ref="example-funcs-defining-by-algorithm" />.
	As the function description involved a multi-step algorithm,
	we should be able to break the steps involved into their own functions,
	then recreate the original functions as a composition.
	</p><p>
	First, define <m>\funcdef{\operatorname{abs}}{\powset{\Z}}{\powset{\N}}</m> by
	<me> \operatorname{abs}(X) = \setdef{\abs{x}}{x \in X} </me>.
	</p><p>
	Next, define <m>\funcdef{\min}{\powset{\N}}{\N}</m> so that <m>\min(X)</m> outputs the minimum number in input set <m>X</m>,
	and outputs <m>0</m> in case <m>X = \emptyset</m>.
	</p><p>
	Finally, define <m>\funcdef{f}{\N}{\N}</m> by <m>f(n) = 2 n + 1</m>.
	</p><p>
	Each of these functions represents one step in the algorithm defining the function in
	<xref ref="example-funcs-defining-by-algorithm" />,
	but to recreate that function we need to compose the functions in the correct order:
	write <m>\varphi = f \funccomp \min \funccomp \operatorname{abs}</m>,
	so that
	<me> \varphi(X) = 2 \min\bbrac{\operatorname{abs}(X)} + 1 </me>
	computes the same result for an input set <m>X</m> as the algorithm described in <xref ref="example-funcs-defining-by-algorithm" />.
	</p>
</example>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-funcs-inverses">
<title>Inverses</title>

<p>
Suppose <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m> is a function.
By definition, <m>f</m> associates an element of <m>B</m> to each element of <m>A</m>.
Sometimes we want to reverse this process: given an element <m>b \in B</m>, can we determine an element <m>a \in A</m> such that <m>f(a) = b</m>?
We'll begin to answer this question by first finding all possible <q>reverse results</q> from elements in subsets of <m>B</m>.
<dl width="narrow">
	<li xml:id="definition-funcs-inverse-set-image">
		<title>inverse image (of a subset <m>C</m> of the codomain <m>B</m>)</title>
		<idx><h>inverse</h><h>image</h><h>of a set</h></idx>
		<idx><h>image</h><h>inverse</h><h>of a set</h></idx>
		<p>
		the set of all domain elements <m>a \in A</m> for function <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m> for which the corresponding output element <m>f(a)</m> lies in the subset <m>C</m> of the codomain
		</p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title><m>\funcinvimg{f}{C}</m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>\funcinvimg{f}{C}</m></usage>
			<description>the inverse image of the subset <m>C \subseteq B</m> under the function <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m></description>
		</notation>
		<p>
		the inverse image of the subset <m>C \subseteq B</m> under the function <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m>,
		so that <me> \funcinvimg{f}{C} = \setdef{a \in A}{f(a) \in C} </me>
		</p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<figure>
	<caption>A Venn diagram of a function inverse image.</caption>
	<image xml:id="image-funcs-inv-image" width="97%">
		<description>A Venn diagram of a function inverse image.</description>
		<latex-image><xi:include href="funcs.d/inv-image.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
	</image>
</figure>

<hypothesis><statement><p>
	<!-- idea -->
	As in the figure above, <m>\funcinvimg{f}{C}</m> collects together all those elements of <m>A</m> whose images under <m>f</m> land inside <m>C</m>.
</p></statement></hypothesis>

<example><title>Some inverse images under sine</title>
	<p> Consider <m>\funcdef{f}{\R}{\R}</m>, <m>f(x) = \sin x</m>. </p>
	<p>
	Then
	<me> \inv{f}\bbrac{\{-1,0,1\}} = \setdef{\frac{m \pi}{2}}{m \in \Z} </me>
	because
	<me> \sin\left(\frac{m \pi}{2}\right) </me>
	will equal <m>0</m> when <m>m</m> is even and will equal <m>1</m> or <m>-1</m> when <m>m</m> is odd,
	and no other input values will produce outputs of <m>0</m>, <m>1</m>, or <m>-1</m>.
	</p><p>
	However, <me> \inv{f}\bbrac{\setdef{y \in \R}{y \gt 1}} = \emptyset </me>
	because there are <em>no</em> input values for sine that will produce an output value greater than <m>1</m>.
	</p>
</example>

<p>
Now let's return to the question of trying to reverse an input-output relationship <m>f(a) = b</m>:
the set <m>\inv{f}\bbrac{\{b\}}</m> collects together all possible candidates for the inverse image of <m>b</m>.
<dl width="narrow">
	<li xml:id="definition-funcs-inverse-element-image">
		<title>inverse image (of an element <m>b</m> of the codomain <m>B</m>)</title>
		<idx><h>inverse</h><h>image</h><h>of an element</h></idx>
		<idx><h>image</h><h>inverse</h><h>of an element</h></idx>
		<p>
		the inverse image <m>\inv{f}\bbrac{\{b\}}</m>,
		which consists of all domain elements <m>a \in A</m> for which <m>f(a) = b</m> 
		</p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title><m>\funcinvimg{f}{b}</m></title>
		<p> simplified notation to mean the inverse image of element <m>b</m> </p>
	</li>
</dl>
This gives us a way to associate to an element <m>b \in B</m> a set <m>\funcinvimg{f}{b}</m> of elements of <m>A</m>.
</p>

<insight><p>
	When does this association <m>b \mapsto \funcinvimg{f}{b}</m> give us a function
	<m>\funcdef{\inv{f}}{B}{A}</m>?
</p></insight>

<p>
There are two possible ways that this will fail to give us a function.
<ol>
	<li>
		Suppose there is an element <m>b \in B</m> such that the set <m>\funcinvimg{f}{b}</m> contains (at least) two distinct elements <m>a_1,a_2</m>.
		Then in general there is no way to choose between <m>\funcinvimg{f}{b} = a_1</m> and <m>\funcinvimg{f}{b} = a_2</m>.
		Therefore, if <m>f</m> is <em>not injective</em>,
		the function <m>\funcdef{\inv{f}}{B}{A}</m> is <em>not well-defined</em>.
	</li>
	<li>
		Suppose there is an element <m>b \in B</m> such that <m>\funcinvimg{f}{b} = \emptyset</m>.
		Then there is <em>no</em> element of <m>A</m> which we can assign to <m>\funcinvimg{f}{b}</m>.
		Therefore, if <m>f</m> is <em>not surjective</em>, the function <m>\funcdef{\inv{f}}{B}{A}</m> is <em>undefined</em> on some elements of <m>B</m>.
	</li>
</ol>
So it seems we will need a function to be <em>bijective</em> in order to be able to reverse the input-output rule to obtain an inverse function.
</p>

<p><dl width="narrow">
	<li>
		<title>inverse function</title>
		<idx><h>function</h><h>inverse</h></idx>
		<idx><h>inverse</h><h>function</h></idx>
		<p>
		for a bijective function <m>f</m>, the <term>inverse function</term> associates to each codomain element of <m>f</m> the corresponding unique domain element that produces it through <m>f</m>
		</p>
	</li>
	<li>
		<title><m>\inv{f}</m></title>
		<notation>
			<usage><m>\funcdef{\inv{f}}{B}{A}</m></usage>
			<description>the inverse function associate to bijective function <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m></description>
		</notation>
		<p>
		the inverse function <m>\funcdef{\inv{f}}{B}{A}</m> for bijective function <m>\funcdef{f}{A}{B}</m>,
		so that for <m>b \in B</m> we have <m>\funcinvimg{f}(b)</m> defined to be the unique element <m>a \in A</m> such that <m>f(a) = b</m>
		</p>
	</li>
</dl></p>

<example><title>An invertible single-variable, real-valued function</title><p>
	The function <m>\funcdef{f}{\R}{\R}</m>, <m>f(x) = x^3</m>, is bijective and has inverse <m>\inv{f}(x) = x^{\frac{1}{3}}</m>.
</p></example>

<example><title>Inverting a numerical encoding of the alphabet</title><p>
	Returning again to the bijection <m>\funcdef{\varphi}{\Sigma}{B}</m>
	encountered in <xref ref="example-funcs-letters-embed-into-numbers" />
	and <xref ref="example-func-identify-letters-numbers" />,
	where
	<md><mrow> \Sigma \amp = \ShortEngAlphabet, \amp B \amp = \{ 1, 2, \dotsc, 26 \}, </mrow></md>
	the inverse function <m>\funcdef{\inv{\varphi}}{B}{\Sigma}</m> associates to each number <m>1 \le b \le 26</m> the corresponding letter at that position of the alphabet.
	For example, <m>\inv{\varphi}(11) = \mathrm{k}</m>.
</p></example>

<example><title>A non-invertible function</title><p>
	The function <m>\funcdef{g}{\R}{\R}</m>, <m>g(x) = x^2</m>,
	does not have an inverse since it is not bijective.
	However, the function <m>\funcdef{h}{\nnegset{\R}}{\nnegset{\R}}</m>, <m>h(x) = x^2</m>,
	so that <m>h = \funcres{g}{\nnegset{\R}}</m> but with codomain also restricted down to the image of <m>g</m>,
	has inverse <m>\inv{h}(x) = \sqrt{x}</m>.
</p></example>

<note><p>
	If <m>f</m> is bijective, then so is <m>\inv{f}</m>, and <m>\inv{f}</m> is the <em>unique</em> function <m>B \to A</m> such that both
	<md><mrow> \inv{f} \funccomp f \amp = \id_A, \amp f \funccomp \inv{f} \amp = \id_B </mrow></md>.
</p></note>

<exercise><p> Prove that if <m>f</m> is bijective then so is <m>\inv{f}</m>, and <m>\inv{(\inv{f})} = f</m>. </p></exercise>

</section>

<xi:include href="./funcs.d/activities.ptx" />
<xi:include href="./funcs.d/exercises.ptx" />

</chapter>
